</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C337088DF765B124B182FC0832C446A7" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B925B06F765B124B182FC0832C446A7" blockId="16.[151,1437,547,1509]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
COMMENTS: 
<typeStatus id="5496E5A4F765B124B00EFC0833BA4753" box="[331,387,1015,1041]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Type</typeStatus>
locality restricted to Dwars Berge (= Dwarsberge), Marico District, 
<collectingRegion id="49E995E4F765B124B5DBFC0837A14753" box="[1182,1432,1015,1041]" country="South Africa" name="North West" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">North West Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33A1B96F765B124B1D2FBE433164777" box="[151,303,1051,1077]" name="South Africa" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F765B124B01AFBE430A94777" author="Gyldenstolpe, N." box="[351,656,1051,1077]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" pagination="264 - 292" refId="ref28785" refString="Gyldenstolpe, N. (1934) The travels and collections of Johan August Wahlberg, 1810 - 1856: a pioneer naturalist in South Africa. Ibis, 76, 264 - 292. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1474 - 919 X. 1934. tb 01567. x" type="journal article" year="1934">Gyldenstolpe (1934: 291)</bibRefCitation>
. Dwarsberge is to the west of Spitskop (1) on 
<figureCitation id="13164783F765B124B5D7FBE436CB4777" box="[1170,1266,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1113,1137]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1088]" captionTargetId="figure-19@17.[151,1436,179,1088]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 3. Wahlberg’s camps and collecting sites (red dots) in the North West Province 1842–1844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541743/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Figure 3</figureCitation>
. The reasoning and basis behind Gyldenstolpe’s restricted 
<typeStatus id="5496E5A4F765B124B33BFBC03097471B" box="[638,686,1087,1113]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">type</typeStatus>
locality and change from the label data is not known. It is almost impossible, given the information in Wahlberg’s journal, to identify the precise 
<typeStatus id="5496E5A4F765B124B557FB9C367B473F" box="[1042,1090,1123,1149]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D2085F765B124B587FB9C37AC473F" authorityName="Sundevall" authorityYear="1850" box="[1218,1429,1123,1149]" class="Aves" family="Motacillidae" genus="Anthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lineiventris">
<emphasis id="B9598714F765B124B587FB9C37AC473F" box="[1218,1429,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Anthus lineiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the label locality of Spitskop (1) should be accepted as the TL. Wahlberg’s movements in September and early October are vague. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F765B124B350FB54308C4787" author="Brinck, P." box="[533,693,1194,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" refId="ref28132" refString="Brinck, P. (1955) Swedish exploration of South African animal life during 200 years. In: Hanstrom, B., Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.), South African Animal Life. Vol. 1. Almquist &amp; Wiksell, Stockholm, pp. 11 - 61." type="book" year="1955">Brinck (1955)</bibRefCitation>
he arrived at Matlapengberg on 
<date id="FF937DC6F765B124B56AFB5437294787" box="[1071,1296,1195,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" value="1843-09-14">14 September 1843</date>
. His journal only records “travel” after leaving the Matlapengberg (
<geoCoordinate id="EE193DC1F765B124B3BBFB3131AF47AB" box="[766,918,1230,1257]" degrees="25" direction="south" minutes="18" orientation="latitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" precision="925" value="-25.3">25° 18’ south</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE193DC1F765B124B2E4FB30361F47AB" box="[929,1062,1230,1257]" degrees="26" direction="east" minutes="45" orientation="longitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" precision="925" value="26.75">26° 45’ east</geoCoordinate>
) on 17 September. However, 
<specimenCount id="9D2B908FF765B124B437FB303335464F" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
collected on 24 September are labelled Matlapengberg, and it may be that he returned to Matlapengberg for a few days, or that the skins are incorrectly dated on the labels. On 28 September he recorded setting off for “Lubblabergen” (Dubblabergen?), an unidentified place that could be Dwarsberge. There are no localities given in the journal between Matlapengberg and Saulspoort, except that he “passed around the end of Leroma [on 9 October] and continued on the other side of the mountain” to (eventually, three days later) reach Saulspoort on 12 October. There is an implication that the night of 9 October was spent at Pilanesberg. The various localities are shown in 
<figureCitation id="13164783F765B124B1D2FA3432CE46A7" box="[151,247,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1113,1137]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1088]" captionTargetId="figure-19@17.[151,1436,179,1088]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 3. Wahlberg’s camps and collecting sites (red dots) in the North West Province 1842–1844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541743/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Figure 3</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
